reviews.review_text: Holy Good God Of Mother The Sugar Magnolia is balls out rock and roll and the finest example of the band at their peak of fun, and shit I have been listening to this shit for 30 fuckin years...

HANDS DOWN Best Wharf Rat EVER It's not a perfect rendition (a miscue following "get up and fly away", and some bum notes from Jerry in his first solo), but if you can overlook these small flaws, you will experience the most powerful performance of this song in existence. Jerry's final solo is the highest, most intense guitar peak I've ever heard, anywhere, anytime, by any musican. An unbelievable, must hear moment, unlike anything he's ever played.

No Jive in Nashville So, by this point in the tour the band was in fine form and good times followed. The punchy first set is full of spirited takes. Check out, for example, the fun groove Jerry builds in the coda of Looks Like Rain (starting around 5:30) and the raucous vocals to top off the set-closing Deal (starting around 4:20), and watch your smile grow. Bob exits with the classic quip: “we quit, see ya’ll later.” Thankfully, they soon returned with another swinging set of well-played standards for the period, culminating in a fierce final solo in Wharf Rat and a sparkling Sugar Magnolia. Long story short, break out your rockin’ shoes and give this terrific show a listen.
